    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="1220"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1220">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894a.01/7–1944</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Director of the Office of European Affairs</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dunn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Director of the Civil Affairs Division,
                        War Department</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hilldring</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="70" xml:id="d1220fn70">Similar letter sent to Capt. H. L.
                        Pence, Navy Department.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-21">July 21,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear General Hilldring</hi>: I am transmitting herewith
                    a series of papers prepared by the State Department on “Military Government <pb
                        facs="1284" n="1272" xml:id="pg_1272"/> in Formosa” relating to political
                    and policy questions presented by the War and Navy Departments.<note n="71"
                        xml:id="d1220fn71">For summary, see PWC–184a, June 28, <ref
                            target="#pg_1266">p. 1266</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>These papers are identical with those which were transmitted earlier with the
                    indication that they represent the informal views of experts in the Department.
                    The papers have since been formally approved at the policy level and may now be
                    regarded as the present views of the Department of State, subject, however, to
                    such modifications as may be necessary in the light of future developments.<note
                        n="72" xml:id="d1220fn72">See PWO-300, September 27, below.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James Clement Dunn</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
